        <name>
            <text>7.4.1.2 Inverse of a matrix</text>
        </name>
        <questiontext format="html">
            <text><![CDATA[
<p class="HELM_exercise">
    <span class="multilang" lang="en">
        Exercise
    </span>
    <span class="multilang" lang="no">
        Oppgave
    </span>
</p>
<p>
    <span class="multilang" lang="en">
        Consider \(A={@A@}\), and let \(B={@B@}\) be a possible inverse of \(A\).
    </span>
    <span class="multilang" lang="no">
        La \(A={@A@}\) v&#230;re gitt, og la \(B={@B@}\) v&#230;re en mulig invers av \(A\).
    </span>
</p>
<ol class="HELM_parts">
    <li>
        <p>
            <span class="multilang" lang="en">
                Find \(AB\) and \(BA\)
            </span>
            <span class="multilang" lang="no">
                Finn \(AB\) og \(BA\)
            </span>
        </p>
        <div>
            \(AB= \) [[input:ans1]] [[validation:ans1]][[feedback:prt1]]
        </div>
        <div>
            <br/>
        </div>
        <div>
            \(BA= \) [[input:ans2]] [[validation:ans2]][[feedback:prt2]]
        </div>
    </li>
    <li>
        <p>
            <span class="multilang" lang="en">
                Equate the elements of \(AB\) to those of \(I={@I@}\) and try to solve the resulting four equations.
            </span>
            <span class="multilang" lang="no">
                Sammenligne elementene til \(AB\) til elementene for \(I={@I@}\) og pr&#248;ve da &#229; l&#248;se de fire likninger som f&#248;lger.
            </span>
        </p>
        <p>
            <span class="multilang" lang="en">
                What does your solution tell you about finding an inverse of \(A\)?
            </span>
            <span class="multilang" lang="no">
                Hva kan du si om inversen til \(A\) mht. l&#248;snigen din?
            </span>
        </p>
    </li>
</ol>
]]></text>
        </questiontext>
        <generalfeedback format="html">
            <text><![CDATA[
<ol class="HELM_parts">
    <li>
        <p>
            For \(A={@A@}\), \(B={@B@}\) the products are
        </p>
        \[AB={@ta1@}, BA={@ta2@}.\]
    </li>
</ol>
<p>
    Equating \(AB=I\) yields
</p>
\[a=1, b=0, a=0, b=1/2.\]
<p>
    This is a contradiction, and hence the matrix \(A\) has no inverse and is said to be a
    <b>
        singular matrix
    </b>
    .
</p>
<p>
    A matrix with an inverse is said to be
    <b>
        non-singular
    </b>
    .
</p>
]]></text>
